e upon Tyne, Northumberland, England":"Newcastle upon Tyne, Northumberland, England","St Mary Woolnoth with St Mary Woolchurch Haw, London, England, United Kingdom":"St Mary Woolnoth with St Mary Woolchurch Haw, London, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","England":"England","Northamptonshire, England":"Northamptonshire, England","Barnstaple, Devon, England":"Barnstaple, Devon, England"},"en":{"1556–1627":"1556–1627","1596–1624":"1596–1624","1600–1622":"1600–1622","1530–1608":"1530–1608","10 August 1556":"10 August 1556","1624":"1624","1569":"1569","1558":"1558","1556":"1556","1622":"1622","1600":"1600","before 28 January 1600":"before 28 January 1600","1620":"1620","1587":"1587","13 June 1622":"13 June 1622","1585":"1585","1530":"1530","1596":"1596","14 August 1627":"14 August 1627","1608":"1608","1627":"1627","Bunny, Nottinghamshire, England":"Bunny, Nottinghamshire, England","Newcastle upon Tyne, Northumberland, England":"Newcastle upon Tyne, Northumberland, England","St Mary Woolnoth with St Mary Woolchurch Haw, London, England, United Kingdom":"St Mary Woolnoth with St Mary Woolchurch Haw, London, England, United Kingdom","England":"England","Northamptonshire, England":"Northamptonshire, England","Barnstaple, Devon, England":"Barnstaple, Devon, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Stevenson","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: from the Middle English and Older Scots personal name <i>Steven</i>, <i>Stephen</i> (see   Steven  ) + <i>-son</i>. This surname is also very common in northern Ireland (especially Antrim and Down), where it has been interchangeable with   Steenson   and   Stinson  . In North America, this surname has also absorbed various European cognates, such as Danish, Norwegian, and North German   Steffensen   or   Stephensen  ; see also   Stevens  .","Scottish: variant of <b>Stevenston</b>, a habitational name from Stevenston (Ayrshire), Stevenson in Newlands (Peeblesshire), or Stevenson in Haddington (East Lothian). The placename in each case derives from the personal name <i>Steven</i> + Older Scots <i>toun</i> ‘farmstead, settlement’.","English: habitational name from Stevenstone (Devon), meaning ‘Stephen's farmstead’."],"variants":[{"name":"Stimpson","meanings":["English:","variant of   Stevenson  , with a progressive shortening of <i>Steven-</i> to <i>Sten-</i>, <i>Stin-</i>, and finally <i>Stimp-</i>. Compare   Stenson  ,   Stinson  .","sometimes perhaps a variant of   Timson   with a prosthetic <i>S-</i>."]},{"name":"Steveson","meanings":["English (Derbyshire): from a shortened form of   Stevenson  ."]},{"name":"Stinson","meanings":["English: shortened form of   Stevenson  . Compare   Steenson   and   Stimpson  ."]},{"name":"Steven","meanings":["Scottish, English, Dutch, and North German: from the personal name <i>Steven</i>, from Latin <i>Stephanus</i>, Greek <i>Stephanos</i> ‘crown’. This was a popular name throughout Christendom in the Middle Ages, having been borne by the first Christian martyr, stoned to death at Jerusalem three years after the death of Christ. In North America, this surname has also absorbed various cognates from other languages, e.g. German   Steffen  , German and Polish   Stefan  , Slovenian and Slovak <b>Štefan</b>, Hungarian <b>István</b> (see   Istvan  ), and also their patronymics and other derivatives (see   Stevens  )."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705202,"age":2,"year":"1558","julianDay":2290108,"title":"Act of Uniformity","description":"The Act of Uniformity was passed by the Parliament of England and required all people to go to church once a week. The consequence of not attending church was a fine of 12 pence, which was a considerable amount for a poor person.","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705205,"age":13,"year":"1569","julianDay":2294126,"title":"State Lottery","description":"A State Lottery was recorded in 1569. The tickets were sold at St. Paul's Cathedral in London.","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705207,"age":29,"year":"1585","julianDay":2299970,"title":"The First English Colony is Established in America","description":"England established its first colony in North America in 1585 as a way to generate additional wealth. The colony was named Virginia, after the virgin Queen Elizabeth I.","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705208,"age":31,"year":"1587","julianDay":2300700,"title":"Elizabeth I Signs Death Warrant for Mary, Queen of Scots","description":"Elizabeth I signed the death warrant for Mary, Queen of Scots, on February 1, 1587, as she was found guilty of plotting to assasinate Elizabeth. Mary, Queen of Scots, was beheaded at Fotheringhay Castle in England on February 8, 1587.","url":"https://www.elizabethi.org/mary_queen_of_scots/","urlTitle":"Elizabeth I.org - Mary Queen of Scots","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705210,"age":44,"year":"1600","julianDay":2305448,"title":"The Honourable East India Company","description":"The Honourable East India Company, a British joint-stock company, was established in 1600 for trade in the Indian Ocean region. At its height, the British East India Company had a private army which was twice the size of the British Army, ruled large sections of India, and revenues in the millions.","url":"https://www.historic-uk.com/HistoryUK/HistoryofEngland/The-East-India-Company/","urlTitle":"Historic UK - The East India Company","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705212,"age":64,"year":"1620","julianDay":2312753,"title":"The Pilgrims Board the Mayflower","description":"\"The Pilgrims boarded the Mayflower in search of religious freedom in the New World in September 1620. The Mayflower set sail from Plymouth, England, with 102 passengers, 40 of whom called themselves \"\"Saints.\"\" After two stormy months at sea, the ship reached the New World. Nearly half of the group died during their first winter due to malnutrition and the harsh New England winter.\"","url":"https://www.themayflowersociety.org/the-pilgrims/pilgrim-history","urlTitle":"The Mayflower Society - Pilgrim History","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"William Stevenson was born in 1556, in Northamptonshire, England as the son of Humffrey Stephens. He had at least 1 daughter with Margareta Dunn. He died in 1627, at the age of 71, and was buried in Bunny, Nottinghamshire, England."},"et":{"1556–1627":"1556–1627","1596–1624":"1596–1624","1600–1622":"1600–1622","1530–1608":"1530–1608","10 August 1556":"10. august 1556","1624":"1624","1569":"1569","1558":"1558","1556":"1556","1622":"1622","1600":"1600","before 28 January 1600":"enne 28. jaanuari 1600","1620":"1620","1587":"1587","13 June 1622":"13. juuni 1622","1585":"1585","1530":"1530","1596":"1596","14 August 1627":"14. august 1627","1608":"1608","1627":"1627","Bunny, Nottinghamshire, England":"Bunny, Nottinghamshire, England","Newcastle upon Tyne, Northumberland, England":"Newcastle upon Tyne, Northumberland, England","St Mary Woolnoth with St Mary Woolchurch Haw, London, England, United Kingdom":"St Mary Woolnoth with St Mary Woolchurch Haw, London, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","England":"England","Northamptonshire, England":"Northamptonshire, England","Barnstaple, Devon, England":"Barnstaple, Devon, England"},"fi":{"1556–1627":"